From: SRB2Kart PS Vita port
Subject: [PATCH 2/3] glRotatef: honour negative axes

`glRotatef(angle, 0.0f, -1.0f, 0.0f)` is perfectly legal OpenGL and extremely
common in older engines. vitaGL only tests `== 1.0f`, so a negative axis is
*silently ignored*: the rotation simply does not happen.

Symptom in the wild: 3D models in SRB2Kart rotated with the camera / appeared
upside down, while sprites were fine. It took an A/B test to even suspect the
matrix code, because nothing errors out -- the rotation is just dropped.

Rotating by -angle around +axis is mathematically identical, so handle it.

(A fully general fix would use an arbitrary-axis rotation matrix; this patch
keeps the existing fast paths and just adds the mirrored ones.)

---
--- a/source/matrices.c
+++ b/source/matrices.c
@@ -138,11 +138,15 @@
 	// Performing rotation on in use matrix depending on user call
 	float rad = DEG_TO_RAD(angle);
 	if (x == 1.0f) {
 		matrix4x4_rotate_x(*matrix, rad);
+	} else if (x == -1.0f) {
+		matrix4x4_rotate_x(*matrix, -rad);
 	}
 	if (y == 1.0f) {
 		matrix4x4_rotate_y(*matrix, rad);
+	} else if (y == -1.0f) {
+		matrix4x4_rotate_y(*matrix, -rad);
 	}
 	if (z == 1.0f) {
 		matrix4x4_rotate_z(*matrix, rad);
 	}
